<br>
1. there was only ONE SARS case detected according to the WHO site.<br>
<br>
2. dinner for two in a decent american chain family restaurants like Dennis', SkyLark, Friday etc cost around up to 3000 yen. note that it's only for dinner, u have to think about breakfast and lunch as well as any snacks in between... also being a tourist u'd probably wanna try some of the native cuisine and sometime they cost even more depending on the restaurant.  100 yen = around 80 or 90 american cents? not sure..<br>
<br>
like i said earlier, the trip to japan isn't the big deal, it's the cost of living that's very high in japan... if u have a host family, that's probably cheaper for u since u've already taken care of the accomodation and food... then put some money on the side to buy omiyage for visiting tourist places like the tokyo disneyland and disney sea which cost around 15000 yen for all day all attraction pass (although comin from america they might pretty much be the same although it's pretty cool listening to mickey and donald speaking japanese) or edomura (some ninja attraction and basically miniature tokyo in edo period) and also the 1st shogun house/grave etc etc.. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=aohjpn>aohjpn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(5/8/03 8:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1100.topic&index=13>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: no..no..yes?</span><hr size=1> WHO reported the cumulative cases of SARS (including probable cases) has been 7054, cumulative death as 506 and average death rate as 15% as of May 8 worldwide.<br>
